<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-073-196 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 160 143</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  Sept 1991 v2 n9 p387(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Saving data from its savior. (possible problems with tape backup)(Hardware Buyer's Guide) (tutorial)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Tape drives have a higher-than-anticipated propensity for makingmistakes.andP;  For one thing, tape media is more likely than floppydisks to contain bad sections or unusable blocks.andP;  Datacompression or high-speed writing to tape increases thepossibility for errors.andP;  What's more, controller conflicts canrender a tape drive useless.andP;  As a result, data-verification anddata-checking software is a must.andP;  Note that most compressionalgorithms are proprietary; data compressed with one vendor'ssoftware can seldom be read by another vendor's tape drive.andO;Preformatted tapes cost about a dollar extra while saving morethan an hour of formatting time; however, users should still checkthe tape with a tape-checking utility to locate bad sectors.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialTape DrivesData IntegrityData CompressionFailureBack-Up SoftwareCartridge Tape.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Buying tips. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>